
The droplet tempererature is increased by the absorption of thermal radiation.
Considering the total mass of absorbing droplets, the ode for average droplet 
temperature is

m c_p dT/dt = Q_abs

With constant conditions, the average droplet temperature in the end should be

dT = dt Q_abs / (m c_p)

By setting dt = 0.01 s, m = 0.01 kg and c_p = 1.0 kJ/kg, the numerical 
value of dT should be equal to the time averaged Q_abs.

--------------------FDS Data-----------------------------
&HEAD CHID='droplet_absorption_cart',TITLE='Cartesian droplet absorption test case' /

&MESH IJK=3,3,3, XB=0.0,3.0,0.0,3.0,0.0,3.0 /

&TIME T_END=.01 DT = 0.00001 / 

&MISC GVEC=0,0,0, Y_CO2_INFTY=0.,HUMIDITY=0./ 

&DUMP NFRAMES=100 /

&RADI RADTMP=1000.
      ANGLE_INCREMENT=1
      TIME_STEP_INCREMENT=1 /

&SURF ID='HOT'
      DEFAULT=.TRUE.
      TMP_FRONT = 1000.
      TAU_T = 0.0 /

&SPEC ID='NITROGEN',CONDUCTIVITY=0.000001,BACKGROUND=.TRUE./

&SPEC ID='WATER VAPOR'
      VAPORIZATION_TEMPERATURE = 1000.
      MELTING_TEMPERATURE = -273.15
      SPECIFIC_HEAT_LIQUID = 1.0
      HEAT_OF_VAPORIZATION = 1000.
      REFERENCE_ENTHALPY=298.15
      SPECIFIC_HEAT=1.      /

&PART ID='drops'
      STATIC = .TRUE.
      SPEC_ID='WATER VAPOR'
      INITIAL_TEMPERATURE = 0.
      DIAMETER=1000.
      MINIMUM_DIAMETER=10.
      SAMPLING_FACTOR=1 /

&INIT N_PARTICLES = 100, 
      MASS_PER_VOLUME = 0.01
      XB = 1,2,1,2,1,2
      PART_ID = 'drops' /

&DEVC QUANTITY='PARTICLE RADIATION LOSS', ID='Absorption', STATISTICS='VOLUME INTEGRAL', XB=0,3,0,3,0,3 /
&DEVC QUANTITY='ADT', PART_ID='drops', ID='ADT', STATISTICS='VOLUME MEAN', XB=1,2,1,2,1,2 /

&TAIL /


